decision_conditions: The development permitted shall be begun before the expiration of three years from the date of this permission.Reason:To comply with Section 91 of the Town and Country Planning Act 1990 (as amended by S.51 of the Planning and Compulsory Purchase Act  2004)

At no time shall the vehicle parking area indicated on drawing No. ^IN; be used for, or in connection with, the sale, hire, servicing or storage of motor vehicles, motor vehicle spares or associated equipment.Reason:To maintain the appearance of the site in particular and the locality in general, and not prejudice the free flow of traffic on the adjoining highway and in accordance with Policy T.13 of the Unitary Development Plan.

Notwithstanding the provisions of the Town and Country Planning (General Permitted Development) Order 1995 (or any Order revoking and re-enacting that Order), no development falling within Class ^IN; in Part 1 of Schedule 2 to that Order shall be carried out without the prior written permission of the Local Planning Authority.Reason:To prevent over development of the site in accordance with Policy H.13 of the Unitary Development Plan.

The development shall not be commenced until details of all boundary fences and walls have been submitted to and approved by the Local Planning Authority and no part of the development shall be occupied until the approved fences and walls for that part have been provided.  The approved fences and walls shall be retained unless the Local Planning Authority gives prior written approval to their removal.Reason:To ensure the satisfactory means of enclosure for the proposed development in the interests of the visual amenity of the area.

No external construction works, deliveries, external running of plant and equipment or internal works audible outside the site boundary shall take place on the site other than between the hours of 0800  to 1800 on Monday to Friday and 0800 to 1300 on Saturday or on Sundays, Public or Bank Holidays without the prior written permission of the Local Planning Authority.Reason:To ensure that the proposed construction work does not cause undue nuisance and disturbance to neighbouring properties at unreasonable hours and in accordance with Policy G.36 of the Unitary Development Plan.

No building construction works shall take place on the site until such time as a landscape plan for the site has been submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority.  This landscape plan shall show any existing or proposed trees, shrubs, hedgerows and grassed areas on the site.Reason:To safeguard and improve the appearance of the area and in order to comply with Section 197 of the Town and Country Planning Act 1990.

The landscaping scheme as approved in accordance with condition 2 shall be carried out in the first planting and seeding seasons following the completion of construction of the buildings to which the landscaping relates.  Any trees or plants which within a period of 5 years from the date of the initial landscaping implementation die, are removed, or become seriously damaged or diseased, shall be replaced by the consent holder in the next planting season with others of similar size and species in accordance with the approved scheme in condition 6 unless the Local Planning Authority gives written consent to any variation.Reason:To secure the provision and retention of the landscaping in the interests of the visual amenity.

No building construction works shall take place until such time as a scheme showing those areas to be hard landscaped and the details of that hard landscaping (including fencing) have been submitted and approved by the Local Planning Authority in writing.  This landscaping plan shall include provision for tactile paving and use of surface treatment to differentiate visitor parking from resident parking.Reason: To ensure that the development is satisfactorily landscaped in order to improve the visual appearance of the area and to ensure that appropriate methods are used to facilitate understanding of the built environment.

The landscaping scheme as approved in accordance with condition 4 shall be carried out prior to the occupation of the buildings to which it relates and continually maintained thereafter in accordance with condition 6 unless the Local Planning Authority gives written consent to any variation.Reason: To secure the provision and retention of the landscaping in the interests of the visual amenity

No building construction works shall take place until such time as a schedule outlining the implementation and maintenance of hard and soft landscaping for a minimum period of five years has been submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority.  Reason:  To ensure the provision and retention of the landscaping in the interests of the visual amenity.

The car parking access and manoeuvring areas indicated on drawing No. A/ph2a/010 dated 14/09/00 shall be constructed and marked out prior to the occupation of the associated buildings and thereafter retained permanently for the accommodation of vehicles of occupiers and visitors to the premises and not used for any other purpose.  The access and manoeuvring areas for plots 6 - 11, 46 - 50, 51 - 56, 57 - 61, 62- 66 and 67 - 71 shall be constructed to allow a minimum of six metres clear straight reversing distance from all carparks to provide for adequate reverse manoeuvring within these areas.The non-adoptable shared surface areas shall be constructed to have 3.0m radius kerbs to allow adequate ingress and egress and shall be constructed to have a 325 Type I granular sub-base, 90mm DBM road base, 60mm DBM base-course, 40mm HRA wearing course.The carriageway providing access to plots 81 - 88 shall be constructed to a minimum of 6.0m.Reason:  To ensure that sufficient off-street parking and manoeuvring areas are provided so as not to prejudice the free flow of traffic on the highway and that they are constructed to an adequate standard.

Building construction work shall not be commenced until a scheme specifying the provisions to be made to control noise emanating from the site during construction works has been submitted to, and approved in writing, by the Local Planning Authority.  This scheme should include details of the construction methods to be employed, for example piling, the duration of such activities, the equipment to be used and the proposed hours of operation.  All construction activities associated with the development shall be carried out in accordance with the recommendations contained in British Standard 5528, Parts 1 and 2, 1984 and Part 4 1986.Reason: To ensure that the proposed construction works does not cause nuisance and disturbance to neighbouring occupiers.

During construction works, no land within 10 metres of the banks of the Buzzards Mouth Sewer shall be used for storage of any solid matter and thereafter no storage of material shall be permitted in this area.Reason: To prevent solid materials from entering the sewer and causing pollution.

Before the development is commenced a detailed site investigation shall be carried out to establish if the site is contaminated, to assess the degree and nature of the contamination present, and to determine its potential for the pollution of the water environment.  The method and extent of this site investigation shall be agreed with the Planning Authority prior to commencement of the work.  Details of appropriate measures to prevent pollution of ground and surface water, including provisions for monitoring, shall then be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority before the development commences.  The development shall then proceed in strict accordance with the measure approved.Reason:  To prevent pollution of the water environment and to protect construction workers from subsoil hazards, the amenity of the locality and in order to quantify any hazards already existing on the site.

No building construction works are to be commenced until detailed drawings are submitted to and approved by the Local Planning Authority indicating at least 28 of the approved dwellings are to be built to lifetime home standards in accordance with the specification set out by the Joseph Rowntree Foundation.Reason:  To comply with the requirement to provide a minimum of 20% of dwelling built to lifetime homes standards.

The houses approved as lifetime homes in accordance with condition No. 14 shall be constructed in accordance with the plans approved under that condition unless otherwise agreed in writing by the Local Planning Authority.Reason:To comply with the requirement to provide a minimum of 20% of dwelling built to lifetime homes standards.

No building construction works are to be commenced until detailed drawings are submitted to and approved by the Local Planning Authority indicating that the internal dimension of all garaging is at least 2.7m x 5.1m.  All garaging on site is to be constructed in accordance with the approved plans.Reason: To ensure that all garaging is able to adequately house a vehicle and hanging door.

No building construction works shall commence until details of dustbin enclosures showing the design, location and external appearance have been submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority.  The approved enclosures shall be provided before the occupation of the buildings to which they relate.Reason:  To provide satisfactory refuse storage provision in the interests of the appearance of the site and locality.

No building construction work shall commence until details / samples of all facing materials to be used in the development have been submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority and no facing materials shall be used in the construction works except those so approved without the further written approval of the Local Planning Authority.Reason:  To safeguard the appearance of the development.

The construction of the foul and surface water drainage systems shall be carried out in accordance with details submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority prior to the construction of any buildings on the site.Reason: To prevent pollution of the water environment.

Any land within 8 metres of the Buzzards Mouth Sewer shall be maintained as a green corridor with no new hard surfaces or built structures.Reason: To allow flood defence work access and provide a buffer for the watercourse.
